  "articleSummary": "The article argues that using a fixed‑choice “Priority” dropdown (e.g., P1‑P4) is a trap that quickly inflates as teams invent ever‑higher levels (P0, P00, etc.), leading to an unmanageable backlog and “priority‑inflation” wars akin to z‑index wars in UI code. It explains why a simple list cannot capture the fluid, multi‑dimensional nature of real‑world prioritization—urgency, business value, risk, and stakeholder perspectives all shift over time. The author recommends alternatives such as a numeric or neutral starting value, composite scoring, or dynamic frameworks like MoSCoW or the Kano model, and urges disciplined archiving of stale tickets. The tone is a mix of informal rant and practical analysis, using the recurring metaphor of “priority inflation” and the z‑index analogy to illustrate the problem. The piece is aimed at engineers, product managers, and Jira admins responsible for backlog grooming and ticket triage.",
